{"id":"project-LICHEN-73ym","title":"aprs_is.rs: recv() can OOM on long line from malicious server","description":"File: rust/lichen-gateway/src/aprs_is.rs
Lines: 309-326

The recv() method uses BufReader::read_line() which has no upper bound on line length. A malicious APRS-IS server (or MITM attacker) could send a very long line without a newline to exhaust memory.

Current code:
```rust
pub fn recv(&mut self) -> Result<Option<String>, AprsError> {
    loop {
        let mut line = String::new();
        match self.reader.read_line(&mut line) {
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

The 30-second read timeout (line 229) provides some protection, but a slow-drip attack sending one byte at a time could keep the connection alive while accumulating a huge string.

Impact: Memory exhaustion DoS when connected to a malicious server.

Fix: Use read_line() with a maximum line length check, or use a fixed-size buffer:
```rust
const MAX_LINE_LEN: usize = 512; // APRS packets are typically < 256 bytes

pub fn recv(&mut self) -> Result<Option<String>, AprsError> {
    loop {
        let mut line = String::new();
        match self.reader.read_line(&mut line) {
            Ok(0) => return Ok(None),
            Ok(_) => {
                if line.len() > MAX_LINE_LEN {
                    return Err(AprsError::ParseError("line too long".to_string()));
                }
                if line.starts_with('#') {
                    continue;
                }
                return Ok(Some(line.trim_end().to_string()));
            }
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```

